<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-836-350  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 836 350.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Sept 10 1990 v24 n37 p49(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Preventing the dreaded 'call' to virus busters. (computer viruses)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Alexander, Michael.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer viruses are becoming more destructive, are harder to getrid of, are better designed and are spreading quicker than ever.andO;Most damages result not from being hit by a virus, but by aninexperienced user trying to rid the microcomputer of the problem.andO;Analysts have identified at least 240 computer viruses thatafflict users in a variety of ways.andP;  Most observers, however, notethat although viruses are increasing, the threat they pose can begreatly diminished by the judicious use of anti-virus software andby corporate policies that restrict employees from running theirown programs on the company's system.andP;  The purchase of anti-virussoftware, which costs around $10 to $15 dollars per machine, isrelatively cheap when one considers that purging viruses can runas much as $4,000.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     MicrocomputersComputer virusesPreventive Maintenance.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>